## Pull requests

Use repository templates from [.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/](../../.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/). Do not invent a one-off PR body when a template applies.

### Choose a template

| Template | Use when |
|----------|----------|
| [lite.md](../../.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/lite.md) | Small PRs: docs-only, single-file chores, tiny fixes, low risk |
| [full.md](../../.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/full.md) | Multi-package work, tokens/registry/cli, UI + template sync, breaking changes, or architectural impact |

When unsure, use `full.md`.

### Base branch

**Default PR target is `dev`, not `main`.**

| Branch | Role |
|--------|------|
| `dev` | Integration branch — open feature/fix PRs here |
| `main` | Production/release — only when the user explicitly requests a PR to `main` |

GitHub's repository default may still be `main`; do not infer the PR base from `gh repo view` or `origin/HEAD` alone. When the user does not specify a base, use `--base dev`.

**Do not touch `main`** — no commits, merges, fast-forwards, or PRs targeting `main` unless the user explicitly requests it.

### Branch and PR order

For non-trivial work, follow [AGENTS.md § Change workflow](../../AGENTS.md#change-workflow):

```txt
branch off dev → implement → docs alignment → PR to dev (last)
```

Open the PR only when the branch is complete. See [AGENTS.md](../../AGENTS.md) for branch policy and verification surfaces.

### Before opening a PR

Run in parallel:

```bash
git status --short
git diff
git log -5 --oneline
git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD
git diff dev...HEAD
```

Then run **`pnpm format:check`** (or `pnpm format` + re-check if it fails). Do not push or open a PR until formatting passes — CI `root-check` fails on the same step.

Confirm the branch is pushed or push only when the user explicitly requests it.

### Fill the template

1. Read the chosen template file from `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/`.
2. Replace HTML comments with concrete content from **all commits** on the branch, not only the latest commit.
3. Check Scope and Change Type boxes that match the diff.
4. Complete Package Boundary, Registry/CLI, Token/Styling, and UI safety sections when those areas are touched; mark **Not applicable** otherwise.
5. Record exact verification commands and results in the Verification table.
6. Delete optional sections that do not apply (per template comments).

PR title should summarize the branch intent; it may differ from a single commit subject when the branch contains multiple commits.

### Create the PR

Use `gh` after the user explicitly requests a PR:

```bash
git push -u origin HEAD
gh pr create --base dev --title "short pr title" --body-file path/to/filled-body.md
```

For a filled body, write the completed template to a temporary file or pass a HEREDOC/`--body` string — do not open a PR with unfilled `<!-- -->` placeholders or empty required sections.

If a PR was opened against the wrong base, fix with `gh pr edit <number> --base dev` (or `--base main` when explicitly requested).

Return the PR URL when done. Do not push unless the user explicitly requests it.

### GitHub labels (required after PR create)

After `gh pr create` succeeds, **always apply labels** with `gh pr edit`. Taxonomy: [docs/contributors/CONTRIBUTING.md](../../docs/contributors/CONTRIBUTING.md) § GitHub labels, manifest [`.github/labels.yml`](../../.github/labels.yml).

**Always apply when opening a PR:**

| Label | When |
|-------|------|
| `type:*` | One — mirrors primary commit type (`type:feat`, `type:fix`, `type:docs`, …) |
| `area:*` | One or more — every primary package/surface touched (see mapping below) |
| `status:ready-for-review` | PR is complete and awaiting review |
| `meta:breaking-change` | Public API, registry install paths, token CSS, or config breaks |

**Do not apply on PRs:** `priority:*` (issues only), `automation:*` (bot PRs only), `meta:good-first-issue`, `meta:help-wanted`.

#### `area:*` mapping

| Label | Paths / trigger |
|-------|-----------------|
| `area:ui` | `packages/ui/**` |
| `area:tokens` | `packages/tokens/**` |
| `area:registry` | `packages/registry/**` |
| `area:cli` | `packages/cli/**` |
| `area:playground` | `apps/playground/**` |
| `area:docs` | `docs/**`, `AGENTS.md`, package READMEs when docs-heavy |
| `area:repo` | Root tooling, `turbo.json`, workspace scripts, `.github/**` |
| `area:agents` | `.agents/skills/**`, agent workflow policy in this skill |

Pick **all areas** that match the diff — cross-package PRs get multiple `area:*` labels.

#### Examples

| PR shape | Labels |
|----------|--------|
| UI-only feature | `type:feat`, `area:ui`, `status:ready-for-review` |
| UI + registry sync | `type:feat`, `area:ui`, `area:registry`, `status:ready-for-review` |
| UI polish + tokens + docs + playground (breaking) | `type:feat`, `area:ui`, `area:tokens`, `area:registry`, `area:docs`, `area:playground`, `meta:breaking-change`, `status:ready-for-review` |
| Docs-only | `type:docs`, `area:docs`, `status:ready-for-review` |
| CI workflow | `type:ci`, `area:repo`, `status:ready-for-review` |
| Git skill / agent workflow | `type:docs`, `area:agents`, `status:ready-for-review` |

#### Command

After PR is created, derive labels from diff/commits, then:

```bash
gh pr edit <number> --add-label "type:feat,area:ui,area:registry,status:ready-for-review"
```

Comma-separated list; no spaces after commas. Add `meta:breaking-change` when applicable.

